%[text] # A04: Drug Classification  -- FDA Approved Drugs vs Everyday Chemicals
%[text] EasyMolKit Analytics  -- Layer 3
%[text] "Does this white powder look like a drug?" In forensic settings, instant judgment based solely on molecular structure is sometimes required.
%[text] In this tutorial, we convert 200 FDA-approved drugs and 30 everyday chemicals into 2048-bit molecular fingerprints and train "drug-likeness" using SVM (Support Vector Machine) and Random Forest.
%[text] We compare accuracy, F1 score, and ROC/AUC to learn how to choose appropriate evaluation metrics for class-imbalanced data.
%[text] ### What You Will Learn in This Tutorial
%[text] - Understand the "$p \\gg n$" problem in fingerprint-based machine learning
%[text] - Learn how to apply PCA as preprocessing for supervised classification
%[text] - Perform binary molecular classification using `fitcsvm()` and `fitcensemble()`
%[text] - Interpret and understand confusion matrix, accuracy, recall, and F1 score
%[text] - Interpret ROC curve and AUC as threshold-independent performance metrics
%[text] - Recognize the impact of class imbalance on accuracy-based evaluation \
%[text] ### Prerequisites
%[text] - Completion of F03 (Fingerprints) and F04 (Similarity) is required
%[text] - Recommended: Understand context with A01 (PCA) and A02 (Clustering)
%[text] - Statistics and Machine Learning Toolbox (`fitcsvm`, `fitcensemble`, `perfcurve`) is required
%[text] - Internet connection is not required
%[text] - Estimated time: 30-45 minutes
%[text] - Execution: Run each section one by one with Ctrl+Enter \
%[text] ### Data: 
%[text] - `data/list/fda_drugs.csv` (200 FDA-approved drugs, ChEMBL CC-BY-SA 3.0), `data/list/everyday_chemicals.csv` (30 household chemicals, PubChem CC0) \
%[text] ### Note on Label Quality
%[text] - Use the dataset source (FDA registered or everyday product) as class labels (drug vs non-drug).
%[text] - Some everyday chemicals like Aspirin, Caffeine, and Ibuprofen are also actual drugs. This is intentional label noise.
%[text] - In actual QSAR (Quantitative Structure-Activity Relationship) classification, experimentally measured activity values are used.
%[text] - Incomplete labels limit the achievable maximum AUC (see Section 6). \
%[text] ### References
%[text] - Cortes & Vapnik (1995) Support-vector networks. *Machine Learning* 20:273-297.
%[text] - Breiman (2001) Random forests. *Machine Learning* 45:5-32.
%[text] - Fawcett (2006) An introduction to ROC analysis. *Pattern Recognition Letters* 27:861-874.
%[text] - Rogers & Hahn (2010) Extended-connectivity fingerprints. *J Chem Inf Model* 50:742-754. \
%%
%[text] ## Section 0: Environment Setup
% Resolve project root (works for Desktop, MCP, and MATLAB Online)
sDir = fileparts(mfilename('fullpath'));
if strlength(sDir) > 0
    addpath(genpath(fullfile(sDir, '..', '..', '..', 'src')));
elseif isfolder(fullfile(pwd, 'src'))
    addpath(genpath(fullfile(pwd, 'src')));
elseif ~isempty(which("logInfo"))
    addpath(genpath(fileparts(fileparts(which("logInfo")))));
end
projectRoot = resolveProjectRoot();
addpath(genpath(fullfile(projectRoot, 'src')));
logSection("A04", "Section 0: Setup", "Analytics L3"); %[output:047e2845]
emk.setup.initPython(); %[output:22bb2982]
%[text] Warm up the Python/RDKit process before executing the main procedure.
mol_warmup = emk.mol.fromSmiles("C");   % Methane -- lightweight
clear mol_warmup;
%%
%[text] ## Section 1: Dataset Loading and Fingerprint Calculation
%[text] ### What is a Fingerprint
%[text] The Morgan fingerprint (ECFP4) represents a molecule as a 2048-bit binary vector.
%[text] Each bit indicates "whether a certain substructure exists in the molecule" as 0/1. The "4" in ECFP4 refers to the diameter (captures structures up to 2 bonds away from each atom). Thus, a single molecule is described by 2048 0/1 values indicating "which substructures it contains."
%[text] ### Application to Machine Learning and the $p \\gg n$ Problem
%[text] Each molecule is represented by a 2048-dimensional bit vector, which serves as the input (features) to the classifier. Let $n$ be the number of molecules and $p$ be the number of features (bits), then in this case $p = 2048$, $n \\approx 230$.
%[text] In situations where $p \\gg n$ (the number of features far exceeds the number of samples), "overfitting" where the model memorizes the training data is likely to occur.
%[text] Many of the 2048 bits are "0 in almost all molecules" or "1 in almost all molecules" and carry little information.
%[text] We address this issue with dimensionality reduction using PCA (Section 2).
%[text] **Label Convention:** 1 = FDA-approved drug compound (from ChEMBL) / 0 = Everyday household chemical (from PubChem)
logSection("A04", "Section 1: Dataset Loading and Fingerprint Calculation", "Analytics L3"); %[output:0b80715f]
FP_RADIUS = 2;
FP_NBITS  = 2048;
FDA_FILE  = "data/list/fda_drugs.csv";
CHEM_FILE = "data/list/everyday_chemicals.csv";
fdaTbl  = readtable(FDA_FILE,  TextType="string");
chemTbl = readtable(CHEM_FILE, TextType="string");
logInfo("FDA-approved drugs: %d rows  |  Everyday chemicals: %d rows", ... %[output:group:38d47a08] %[output:7eb50b6a]
    height(fdaTbl), height(chemTbl)); %[output:group:38d47a08] %[output:7eb50b6a]
%[text] Parse FDA-approved drugs and calculate fingerprints (Class 1).
fps1 = {}; names1 = string.empty; failed1 = 0;
for k = 1:height(fdaTbl)
    try
        mol = emk.mol.fromSmiles(fdaTbl.SMILES(k));
        fps1{end+1}   = emk.fingerprint.morgan(mol, Radius=FP_RADIUS, NBits=FP_NBITS); %#ok<AGROW>
        names1(end+1) = fdaTbl.Name(k); %#ok<AGROW>
    catch
        failed1 = failed1 + 1;
    end
end
logInfo("FDA Class:     %d successfully parsed, %d failed", numel(fps1), failed1); %[output:5c1ad936]
%[text] Parse everyday chemicals and calculate fingerprints (Class 0).
fps0 = {}; names0 = string.empty; failed0 = 0;
for k = 1:height(chemTbl)
    try
        mol = emk.mol.fromSmiles(chemTbl.SMILES(k));
        fps0{end+1}   = emk.fingerprint.morgan(mol, Radius=FP_RADIUS, NBits=FP_NBITS); %#ok<AGROW>
        names0(end+1) = chemTbl.CommonName(k); %#ok<AGROW>
    catch
        failed0 = failed0 + 1;
    end
end
logInfo("Non-drug Class:     %d successfully parsed, %d failed", numel(fps0), failed0); %[output:36bd3766]
%[text] Assemble the bit matrix and label vector.
n1     = numel(fps1);
n0     = numel(fps0);
nTotal = n1 + n0;
bitMat = zeros(nTotal, FP_NBITS, "single");
allFps = [fps1, fps0];
for j = 1:nTotal
    bitMat(j, :) = single(emk.fingerprint.toArray(allFps{j}));
end
labels   = [ones(n1, 1); zeros(n0, 1)];    % 1=drug, 0=non-drug
allNames = [names1(:); names0(:)];
logInfo("Total: %d molecules (%d drugs, %d non-drugs)", nTotal, n1, n0); %[output:4ad2f284]
logInfo("Class balance: Drugs %.1f%% vs Non-drugs %.1f%%", ... %[output:group:9698b543] %[output:855913f1]
    100*n1/nTotal, 100*n0/nTotal); %[output:group:9698b543] %[output:855913f1]
%%
%[text] ## Section 2: Dimensionality Reduction with PCA
%[text] With fingerprints computed for all molecules, we apply PCA to reduce the 2048-bit vectors to a manageable number of dimensions, mitigating the risk of overfitting when $p \\gg n$.
%[text] Projecting onto the first two PCs also lets us assess visually how well-separated the two classes are.
%[text] ### Why perform PCA before classification
%[text] Many of the 2048 bits are "almost constant" and carry little information.
%[text] PCA finds the directions with the greatest variance (principal components) and compresses the 2048-bit vector to $N\_{PCS}$ dimensions (same approach as PCA on descriptors in A01).
%[text] This automatically removes "almost constant" bits, reducing the feature matrix from $n \\times 2048$ to $n \\times N\_{PCS}$.
%[text] **Choosing** $N\_{PCS}$**:** In fingerprint-based machine learning, 10 to 50 principal components are recommended in the literature. Here, we use $N\_{PCS} = 20$.
%[text] **Important Rule  -- No Data Leakage:** PCA must be fitted only on the training data, and the same transformation must be applied to the test data.
%[text] Fitting PCA on the entire dataset before splitting is called "data leakage" and is prohibited as it overestimates model performance.
logSection("A04", "Section 2: Dimensionality Reduction with PCA", "Analytics L3"); %[output:6b6d89fd]
N_PCS = 20;
%[text] Center the features (scaling is unnecessary  -- binary features are already in the $\[0,\\ 1\]$ range).
bitMean   = mean(bitMat, 1);
bitMat_c  = double(bitMat) - bitMean;
%[text] Columns of binary fingerprints may be linearly dependent, causing `pca()` to issue warnings.
%[text] This is normal behavior and does not affect the accuracy of the results. Suppress warnings and proceed.
pca_ws = warning('off', 'stats:pca:ColRankDefX');
[pcCoeff, pcScore, ~, ~, explained] = pca(bitMat_c, NumComponents=N_PCS);
warning(pca_ws);
logInfo("PCA: Top %d PCs explain %.1f%% of fingerprint variance", ... %[output:group:6dbb5eee] %[output:466a825c]
    N_PCS, sum(explained(1:N_PCS))); %[output:group:6dbb5eee] %[output:466a825c]
%[text] Plot a scatter plot of the first 2 principal components (PC1 and PC2) colored by class.
%[text] If the two classes are visually separated, it indicates that the fingerprints capture "drug-likeness."
figure("Name", "A04 Fingerprint PCA"); %[output:3ac8a987]
hold on; %[output:3ac8a987]
scatter(pcScore(labels==1, 1), pcScore(labels==1, 2), 40, [0.3 0.6 0.9], ... %[output:3ac8a987]
    "filled", MarkerFaceAlpha=0.6, DisplayName="FDA Approved Drugs (Class 1)"); %[output:3ac8a987]
scatter(pcScore(labels==0, 1), pcScore(labels==0, 2), 70, [0.9 0.4 0.3], ... %[output:3ac8a987]
    "^", "filled", MarkerFaceAlpha=0.9, DisplayName="Household Chemicals (Class 0)"); %[output:3ac8a987]
hold off; %[output:3ac8a987]
xlabel(sprintf("PC1 (%.1f%%)", explained(1))); %[output:3ac8a987]
ylabel(sprintf("PC2 (%.1f%%)", explained(2))); %[output:3ac8a987]
title("ECFP4 Fingerprint PCA -- Drugs vs Non-Drugs"); %[output:3ac8a987]
legend(Location="best"); %[output:3ac8a987]
grid on; %[output:3ac8a987]
%%
%[text] ## Section 3: Stratified Training/Test Split
%[text] With the PCA representation ready, we now split the data into a training set and a test set. Because the classes are imbalanced (approximately 87% drugs, 13% non-drugs), we use a **stratified split** to preserve the class ratio in both sets.
%[text] ### What is Stratified Split
%[text] A simple random 80/20 split might accidentally result in the test set containing very few of the minority class (non-drugs).
%[text] In a stratified split, each class is independently split randomly, maintaining the same drug/non-drug ratio in both the training and test sets as in the original data.
%[text] ### Correct PCA Procedure in Classification
%[text] In Section 2, PCA was fitted on all data for visualization purposes.
%[text] In the actual procedure for training a classification model, PCA is fitted on **training data only**, and that transformation is applied to the test data.
logSection("A04", "Section 3: Stratified Training/Test Split", "Analytics L3"); %[output:2f111983]
TEST_RATIO = 0.20;
rng(42);
cvPart   = cvpartition(labels, Holdout=TEST_RATIO);
trainIdx = training(cvPart);
testIdx  = test(cvPart);
%[text] Fit PCA on training data only, and apply the same transformation to the test data.
trainMean = mean(double(bitMat(trainIdx, :)), 1);
Xtrain_c  = double(bitMat(trainIdx, :)) - trainMean;
pca_ws2 = warning('off', 'stats:pca:ColRankDefX');
[pcCoeffTr, XTrain, ~, ~, explainedTr] = pca(Xtrain_c, NumComponents=N_PCS);
warning(pca_ws2);
%[text] Apply the same transformation (centering and projection onto principal component directions) to the test data.
Xtest_c = double(bitMat(testIdx, :)) - trainMean;
XTest   = Xtest_c * pcCoeffTr;   % project onto training PCs
yTrain = labels(trainIdx);
yTest  = labels(testIdx);
logInfo("Training: %d samples (%d drugs, %d non-drugs)", ... %[output:group:6d452980] %[output:5036ab22]
    sum(trainIdx), sum(yTrain==1), sum(yTrain==0)); %[output:group:6d452980] %[output:5036ab22]
logInfo("Testing: %d samples (%d drugs, %d non-drugs)", ... %[output:group:9491c930] %[output:9753c67f]
    sum(testIdx), sum(yTest==1), sum(yTest==0)); %[output:group:9491c930] %[output:9753c67f]
logInfo("Training PCA: Top %d PCs explain %.1f%% of training variance", ... %[output:group:35dd8608] %[output:14180b37]
    N_PCS, sum(explainedTr(1:N_PCS))); %[output:group:35dd8608] %[output:14180b37]
%%
%[text] ## Section 4: SVM Classifier (fitcsvm)
%[text] With training and test sets in hand, we now train an SVM (Support Vector Machine) that finds the maximum-margin boundary between classes. We examine prediction quality using a confusion matrix.
%[text] ### What is SVM
%[text] SVM (Support Vector Machine) is a method that finds a boundary (hyperplane) that separates two classes with the "widest margin."
%[text] If the normal vector of the boundary is $w$, the margin width is expressed as $\\frac{2}{||w||}$.
%[text] Maximizing the margin is equivalent to minimizing $||w||^2$, which is the core of the SVM optimization problem.
%[text] The points closest to the boundary are called "support vectors," and only these points determine the decision boundary.
%[text] ### Explanation of Key Parameters
%[text:table]{"ignoreHeader":true}
%[text] | Parameter | Meaning |
%[text] | --- | --- |
%[text] | `BoxConstraint` (value $C$) | Trade-off between margin width and training error. Small $C$ means wide margin (simple model), large $C$ means narrow margin (fine boundary) |
%[text] | `KernelFunction="linear"` | Uses a linear kernel. Draws a linear boundary in the low-dimensional space after PCA |
%[text] | `Standardize=true` | Normalizes each feature to mean 0 and standard deviation 1 |
%[text:table]
%[text] ### Attention to Class Imbalance
%[text] If drugs are 87% and non-drugs are 13%, simply predicting "all as drugs" yields an accuracy of 87%.
%[text] SVM tends to minimize the total number of misclassifications by default, often ignoring the minority class (non-drugs).
%[text] Be sure to check not only accuracy but also precision, recall, and F1 score.
logSection("A04", "Section 4: SVM Classifier (fitcsvm)", "Analytics L3"); %[output:160add3f]
svmModel = fitcsvm(XTrain, yTrain, ...
    KernelFunction="linear", ...
    BoxConstraint=1.0, ...
    Standardize=true, ...
    ClassNames=[0; 1]);
[yPred_svm, scores_svm] = predict(svmModel, XTest);
%[text] Manually calculate classification evaluation metrics (no additional toolbox functions required).
cm_svm   = confusionmat(yTest, yPred_svm, Order=[0, 1]);
acc_svm  = sum(diag(cm_svm)) / sum(cm_svm(:));
prec_svm = cm_svm(2,2) / max(cm_svm(1,2) + cm_svm(2,2), 1);  % avoid /0
rec_svm  = cm_svm(2,2) / max(cm_svm(2,1) + cm_svm(2,2), 1);
f1_svm   = 2 * prec_svm * rec_svm / max(prec_svm + rec_svm, eps);
logInfo("SVM (linear, C=1) -- Test Set:"); %[output:2a791e7d]
logInfo("  Accuracy=%.3f  Precision=%.3f  Recall=%.3f  F1=%.3f", ... %[output:group:9109653d] %[output:37bba706]
    acc_svm, prec_svm, rec_svm, f1_svm); %[output:group:9109653d] %[output:37bba706]
logInfo("  Confusion Matrix: TN=%d FP=%d FN=%d TP=%d", ... %[output:group:3983e92a] %[output:3eb3dc6b]
    cm_svm(1,1), cm_svm(1,2), cm_svm(2,1), cm_svm(2,2)); %[output:group:3983e92a] %[output:3eb3dc6b]
figure("Name", "A04 SVM Confusion Matrix"); %[output:30acd2e7]
confusionchart(categorical(yTest, [0 1], ["Non-drug","Drug"]), ... %[output:group:7040b02a] %[output:30acd2e7]
    categorical(yPred_svm, [0 1], ["Non-drug","Drug"]), ... %[output:30acd2e7]
    ColumnSummary="column-normalized", RowSummary="row-normalized", ... %[output:30acd2e7]
    Title="SVM Confusion Matrix"); %[output:group:7040b02a] %[output:30acd2e7]
logInfo("Displayed SVM Confusion Matrix"); %[output:504e7c93]
%[text] ### Understanding the Confusion Matrix and Evaluation Metrics
%[text] The confusion matrix is a 2x2 table of "Actual Label x Predicted Label."
%[text:table]{"ignoreHeader":true}
%[text] | Cell | Abbreviation | Meaning |
%[text] | --- | --- | --- |
%[text] | True Negative | TN | Correctly predicted "Non-drug" as non-drug |
%[text] | False Positive | FP | Incorrectly predicted "Drug" as non-drug ("False Alarm") |
%[text] | False Negative | FN | Incorrectly predicted "Non-drug" as drug ("Miss") |
%[text] | True Positive | TP | Correctly predicted "Drug" as drug |
%[text:table]
%[text] Each metric is calculated from the values in the confusion matrix as follows.
%[text] - **Precision:** The proportion of actual drugs among those predicted as "Drug" $= \\frac{TP}{TP + FP}$
%[text] - **Recall:** The proportion of actual drugs correctly predicted as "Drug" $= \\frac{TP}{TP + FN}$
%[text] - **F1 Score:** The harmonic mean of precision and recall $= \\frac{2 \\times Precision \\times Recall}{Precision + Recall}$ \
%[text] In the context of drug screening, the cost of FN (missing a drug) may be higher than FP (false alarm).
%%
%[text] ## Section 5: Random Forest Classifier (fitcensemble)
%[text] With the SVM baseline in place, we now train a Random Forest -- an ensemble of decision trees -- and compare it against SVM on class imbalance handling and feature importance.
%[text] ### What is a Random Forest?
%[text] A Random Forest is a method (ensemble learning) that combines many decision trees for prediction.
%[text] It is the same tree ensemble approach as in A03's regression problem, but this time each tree "votes" for a class.
%[text] The algorithm flow is as follows.
%[text] - Train $B$ decision trees with different bootstrap samples (random sampling with replacement)
%[text] - At each tree split, use only a randomly chosen subset of features (to prevent overfitting)
%[text] - Each tree outputs a class vote (0 or 1), and the final prediction is determined by majority vote
%[text] - Class probabilities are obtained as the proportion of trees voting for that class (e.g., 170 out of 200 trees vote "drug" -\> probability 0.85) \
%[text] ### Advantages of Random Forest over SVM
%[text] It can output probability scores directly, which can be used in ROC curves (Section 6).
%[text] It is less sensitive to feature scaling, so `Standardize` is not needed.
%[text] Simply specifying `Prior="uniform"` can handle class imbalance easily.
%[text] The contribution of each feature (PC) to discrimination can be visualized as "feature importance."
%[text] ### Explanation of Key Parameters
%[text] `Prior="uniform"` sets the prior class probabilities to 0.5/0.5. Regardless of the actual ratio (87%/13%), it treats both classes equally, improving recall for the minority class (non-drug).
%[text] `MinLeafSize=1` allows the decision trees to grow maximally (most complex model). If there are many samples, increase the value to prevent overfitting.
logSection("A04", "Section 5: Random Forest Classifier (fitcensemble)", "Analytics L3"); %[output:881018e3]
rfClf = fitcensemble(XTrain, yTrain, ...
    Method="Bag", ...
    NumLearningCycles=200, ...
    Learners=templateTree(MinLeafSize=1), ...
    Prior="uniform", ...     % Handle class imbalance
    ClassNames=[0; 1]);
[yPred_rf, scores_rf] = predict(rfClf, XTest);
cm_rf   = confusionmat(yTest, yPred_rf, Order=[0, 1]);
acc_rf  = sum(diag(cm_rf)) / sum(cm_rf(:));
prec_rf = cm_rf(2,2) / max(cm_rf(1,2) + cm_rf(2,2), 1);
rec_rf  = cm_rf(2,2) / max(cm_rf(2,1) + cm_rf(2,2), 1);
f1_rf   = 2 * prec_rf * rec_rf / max(prec_rf + rec_rf, eps);
logInfo("Random Forest (200 trees, uniform prior) -- Test Set:"); %[output:744d0171]
logInfo("  Accuracy=%.3f  Precision=%.3f  Recall=%.3f  F1=%.3f", ... %[output:group:2568da7f] %[output:75ae4e84]
    acc_rf, prec_rf, rec_rf, f1_rf); %[output:group:2568da7f] %[output:75ae4e84]
logInfo("  Confusion Matrix: TN=%d FP=%d FN=%d TP=%d", ... %[output:group:8ec0e059] %[output:9dd40dac]
    cm_rf(1,1), cm_rf(1,2), cm_rf(2,1), cm_rf(2,2)); %[output:group:8ec0e059] %[output:9dd40dac]
figure("Name", "A04 RF Confusion Matrix"); %[output:3dd1d943]
confusionchart(categorical(yTest, [0 1], ["Non-drug","Drug"]), ... %[output:group:322fd765] %[output:3dd1d943]
    categorical(yPred_rf, [0 1], ["Non-drug","Drug"]), ... %[output:3dd1d943]
    ColumnSummary="column-normalized", RowSummary="row-normalized", ... %[output:3dd1d943]
    Title="Random Forest Confusion Matrix"); %[output:group:322fd765] %[output:3dd1d943]
logInfo("Displayed RF Confusion Matrix"); %[output:7e115610]
%[text] Visualize feature importance (per PCA component) with a bar graph.
%[text] You can see which principal components are most useful for distinguishing drug/non-drug.
featureImp = predictorImportance(rfClf);
figure("Name", "A04 RF Feature Importance (PCA Components)"); %[output:70b8f2b5]
bar(featureImp, FaceColor=[0.4 0.7 0.4]); %[output:70b8f2b5]
xlabel("PCA Component"); ylabel("MDI Importance"); %[output:70b8f2b5]
title("RF Feature Importance for PC1..PC20"); %[output:70b8f2b5]
grid on; %[output:70b8f2b5]
%[text] MDI (Mean Decrease in Impurity) importance represents the average information contribution of each feature to tree decisions.
%[text] Notice that PC1 -- the direction of greatest variance -- does not necessarily have the highest discriminative power. Large variance may reflect within-class diversity rather than between-class difference.
%%
%[text] ## Section 6: Comparison of ROC Curves
%[text] With both classifiers trained, we now compare them using AUC (Area Under the ROC Curve) -- a threshold-independent metric that remains reliable even under class imbalance.
%[text] ### What is an ROC Curve?
%[text] A binary classifier outputs a score (probability or decision value) and converts it to 0/1 using a threshold (default 0.5).
%[text] Changing the threshold alters the balance between true positive rate (TPR) and false positive rate (FPR).
%[text] - Increasing the threshold -\> makes it harder to predict "drug" -\> decreases recall (TPR), increases precision
%[text] - Decreasing the threshold -\> makes it easier to predict "drug" -\> increases recall (TPR), decreases precision \
%[text] An ROC curve plots the true positive rate (TPR = sensitivity) against the false positive rate (FPR = 1 - specificity) for all thresholds.
%[text] ### Interpretation of AUC (Area Under the ROC Curve)
%[text] AUC is the area under the ROC curve, ranging from 0 to 1.
%[text] The standard AUC interpretation guidelines are:
%[text:table]{"ignoreHeader":true}
%[text] | AUC Value | Meaning |
%[text] | --- | --- |
%[text] | 1\.0 | Perfect classifier (zero misclassification at all thresholds) |
%[text] | 0\.9-1.0 | Excellent model |
%[text] | 0\.7-0.9 | Practically good model |
%[text] | 0\.6-0.7 | Marginally useful |
%[text] | 0\.5 | Random classifier (no discriminative power, diagonal line) |
%[text] | Below 0.5 | Poor (check for label noise or bugs) |
%[text:table]
%[text] AUC measures the overall discriminative ability of the model, independent of thresholds, making it more reliable than accuracy in class imbalance situations.
%[text] ### Upper Limit of AUC Due to Label Noise
%[text] Some household chemicals like Aspirin and Caffeine are actually drugs (mislabelled as class 0), making AUC = 1.0 theoretically unattainable.
%[text] Remember that label quality limits the achievable maximum AUC.
%[text] ### Shape of ROC Curve with Small Samples
%[text] Since there are only 6 non-drug samples in the test set, the FPR axis can only take 7 steps: $0,\\ \\frac{1}{6},\\ \\frac{2}{6},\\ldots$.
%[text] Therefore, the ROC becomes a "step function" rather than a smooth curve. This is not an implementation error but normal behavior for small test sets.
logSection("A04", "Section 6: Comparison of ROC Curves", "Analytics L3"); %[output:56809c20]
%[text] The SVM `scores_svm` has 2 columns, with column 2 being the decision value for class 1 (drug). Higher values indicate more "drug-like."
scoreSVM = scores_svm(:, 2);
%[text] The Random Forest `scores_rf` is ordered as `ClassNames=[0;1]`, so column 1 is P(class 0), and column 2 is the posterior probability P(class 1 = drug).
scoreRF  = scores_rf(:, 2);
[xSVM, ySVM, ~, aucSVM] = perfcurve(yTest, scoreSVM, 1);
[xRF,  yRF,  ~, aucRF]  = perfcurve(yTest, scoreRF,  1);
figure("Name", "A04 ROC Curve"); %[output:865f32ae]
hold on; %[output:865f32ae]
plot(xSVM, ySVM, Color=[0.3 0.6 0.9], LineWidth=2, ... %[output:865f32ae]
    DisplayName=sprintf("SVM Linear (AUC=%.3f)", aucSVM)); %[output:865f32ae]
plot(xRF,  yRF,  Color=[0.4 0.7 0.4], LineWidth=2, ... %[output:865f32ae]
    DisplayName=sprintf("Random Forest (AUC=%.3f)", aucRF)); %[output:865f32ae]
plot([0 1], [0 1], "--k", LineWidth=1, DisplayName="Random Baseline (AUC=0.500)"); %[output:865f32ae]
hold off; %[output:865f32ae]
xlabel("False Positive Rate (1 - Specificity)"); %[output:865f32ae]
ylabel("True Positive Rate (Sensitivity / Recall)"); %[output:865f32ae]
title("ROC Curve -- Drug vs Non-Drug Classification"); %[output:865f32ae]
legend(Location="southeast"); %[output:865f32ae]
grid on; axis square;   % Square aspect; unlike axis equal, maintains xlim/ylim at [0,1] %[output:865f32ae]
xlim([0 1]); ylim([0 1]); %[output:865f32ae]
%[text] Display a summary table of evaluation metrics for both models.
summaryTbl = table( ...
    ["SVM (Linear)"; "Random Forest"], ...
    [acc_svm;  acc_rf],  ...
    [prec_svm; prec_rf], ...
    [rec_svm;  rec_rf],  ...
    [f1_svm;   f1_rf],   ...
    [aucSVM;   aucRF],   ...
    VariableNames=["Model","Accuracy","Precision","Recall","F1","AUC"]);
logInfo("Performance Summary:"); %[output:5d638d91]
disp(summaryTbl); %[output:1706f9cf]
logInfo("ROC AUC: SVM=%.3f  RF=%.3f", aucSVM, aucRF); %[output:98b45d4a]
%[text] ### Summary
%[text] - In a $p \\gg n$ situation with 2048 bits and about 230 molecules, dimensionality reduction via PCA is necessary before SVM.
%[text] - In class imbalance, accuracy can be misleading, so use AUC and F1 score.
%[text] - Address class imbalance with `Prior="uniform"` in Random Forest and cost weighting in SVM.
%[text] - AUC is a comprehensive metric of discriminative ability independent of thresholds.
%[text] - Label quality limits the achievable maximum AUC.
%[text] - Always validate implementation correctness with a null model (reshuffle labels and rerun). \

